canonical:
  title: 仲容兄以余將赴召遙贐以詩豈知余之病不能進次韻奉寄
  author: 金宗直
  language: lzh
  text: 老大襟懷易自傷鴒原一日九回腸宦情莫莫同鷄肋雲路冥冥送鴈行詩喩二蟲蘇內翰琴傳一女蔡中郞會須杖策凝川曲棹盡𦨻船擘蠏黃
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 仲容兄以余將赴召遙贐以詩豈知余之病不能進次韻奉寄
  author: 金宗直
  language: lzh
  text: 老大襟懷易自傷。鴒原一日九回腸。宦情莫莫同鷄肋。雲路冥冥送鴈行。詩喩二蟲蘇內翰。琴傳一女蔡中郞。會須杖策凝川曲。棹盡𦨻船擘蠏黃。
korean:
  title: 중용 형이 내가 장차 임금이 부르는데 가게 되므로 멀리 시로써 주나, 어찌 내가 병들어 가지 못함을 알리오. 차운하여 부치노라
  author: 김종직
  language: kor
  text: |-
    늙어지면 그 심회가 스스로 상하기 쉽나니
    하루에 영원(형제) 일은 아홉 번 창자 틀리네
    벼슬하려는 심정이 막막하기 계륵과 같고
    구름 길은 명명한데 기러기 행렬을 보낸다
    시를 두 벌레에 비유했으니 소내한이요
    거문고를 한 딸에게 전했으니 채중랑이다
    우리 모이면 응천 굽이를 산보하다가
    뱃놀이가 끝나거든 해왕(게 장)을 쪼개보세
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1430_010_0760&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 거문고를 …… 채중랑(蔡中郞)이다 : '
    value: 채중랑(蔡中郞)은 한나라 말년에 유명한 문사(文士)  채옹(蔡邕)이라는 사람이었는데, 그도 거문고를 잘하였다. 그 거문고는 그 딸 채염(蔡琰)이 계승하였으므로 그런 말이 있게 되었다.
english:
  title: In Response to Elder Brother Jongyong's Farewell Poem, As He Sends Me Off to the Royal Summons, Though My Illness Prevents My Going
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Growing old, the heart grows tender and easily wounded.
    In one day, the separation of brothers turns my bowels nine times over.
    My yearning for office feels hollow as chicken ribs.
    Through misty clouds the geese fly in formation.

    Poets have likened themselves to insects—as did Su Neihe.
    The zither passed to a daughter—as with Cai Zhonglang.
    When we meet again, we'll stroll the bends of Eungcheon,
    And when our boat ride ends, we'll crack open crab shells together.
  footnotes:
    - 'Su Neihe (蘇內翰) and Cai Zhonglang (蔡中郞) are classical allusions: the former refers to poetic self-portraiture through insect imagery, while the latter refers to the celebrated Han scholar Cai Yong, whose musical mastery of the zither was inherited by his daughter Cai Yan—a metaphor for cultural and personal transmission.'
    - Chicken ribs (計肋) is a classical metaphor for something tasteless and worthless, here describing the hollow pursuit of official position.
    - The poem is written in response to another's verse, maintaining the same rhyme scheme (次韻).
